title: For Sale:  Spanish-made "Ruby" gun – Almost an Antique – 7.65/.32 Auto
postcontent:
Trying to beat the new restrictions on sales between individuals  coming from Obama!

My father returned from WW II with this sweet, old pistol. He probably picked it up from someone in the French military. After WW I, France asked manufacturers in Spain to create a carry gun for its military. Dozens of Spanish factories built guns of this design.

For the complete story on these guns, see:
http://www.reenactor.net/units/151ri/weps/ruby_pistol.htm

This gun was made by La Industria Orbea, Eibar, Spain. That's what the fading etching on the side of the slide indicates (above the "CAL 7.65" marking). Beneath the right end of the slide is a stamped "IO" inside an oval. That indicates the gun was made by Industrie Orbea. The same logo appears on the bottom of the clip, which shows it is original.

At the base of the handle are stamped two stars, "**." This indicates the gun was used by the French military.

At the back of the slide is an engraved "TC" that looks like the logo on the caps of the Minnesota Twins. I have diminished its appearance with a dose from a Gun Blue Pen from Birchwood Casey.

The gun comes with an authentic military type holster with the flap over the gun and a pocket for the clip. I am also including the hard plastic case in which it is set for the photo. For a local sale, I will include about 1 1/2 boxes of .32 Auto ammo.

I also have for sale a brown leather holster my father usually kept the gun in. It's vintage, from Brauer Bros. in St. Louis. Those go for about $40 on eBay.

I just took the one photo because I wanted to get this uploaded as soon as possible. I will take more if someone requests them.

Asking price is for local pick up. If I have to ship it to your FFL holder, the cost should be an additional around $45. That's what it cost when I shipped a pistol last month.
